Exercise Description
Have you ever wondered how recommendation systems work to find the perfect movie for you? Behind these services lies a powerful technique: vector embeddings.

In this exercise, you’ll explore how recommendation systems use embeddings to find movies that match your interests. When you type a query like “science fiction with action,” the system converts both your query and each movie into vectors in a multidimensional space. Using cosine similarity, the system finds the movies closest to your query—a form of approximate search that enables fast and efficient retrieval.

The interface uses the multilingual-e5-small model to generate 384-dimensional embeddings from queries. Similarly, each movie already has a pre-computed embedding based on its title and description.

Challenge
You are given a target permutation — the first 5 movies we want to appear at the top of the results. Your goal is to find an embedding (a 384-dimensional vector) that will rank the movies so that these 5 movies appear first, and in the correct order!

How well can you "trick" the system? Can you find the perfect embedding that will bring the right movies to the top?

Note: The interface needs to download the model weights, which are hundreds of MB in size. The initial download may take some time.

Scoring System
The scoring system is based on classification accuracy and the score difference between consecutive movies:

Base Score (up to 50 points):

If a target movie is in the top 5 positions: 5 points
If a target movie is in the correct position: 10 points (replaces the 5 points)
Maximum base score: 50 points (5 movies × 10 points)
Bonus (up to 50 points):

Calculated only if all 5 target films are in the top 5 positions and in the correct order
Based on the minimum score difference between consecutive films (1st-2nd, 2nd-3rd, 3rd-4th, 4th-5th, 5th-6th)
If the minimum difference reaches the level threshold: full bonus of 50 points (total = 100%)
Otherwise: linear scale based on the level threshold

